The majority of women in Cuba are for abortion despite the fact that since its implementation in 1968, the abortion rate per 1,000 women between the ages of 15 and 44 has quadrupled, and the death rate as a result continues to rise.

The loss of life for children in the womb is chilling as the statistic per 1,000 live births now stands at 2-4 times greater than other Latin American countries such as El Salvador, Peru, and Ecuador, according to Current Digest of the Post-Soviet Press.

Then, the reentry of pro-life groups, led by the Ladies in White, gives many Cubans hope, and International Women’s Group President Maria Astral Hernandez notes the growing movement.

"The Cuban people will never understand the valuable points of view of the Right-to-Life, about forming character, about the value of human practices that lead to the person, and especially the social development of the nation,” she said.

The Ladies in White, groups of powerful women, many imprisoned political activists, have launched a new Pro-Life movement at rallies across the country by giving out flowers to the young Cuban women.
